@NODE OPIS

  WolnyCD is a tool that allows you to set read-speed of your CD-ROM
(CD-R/CD-RW). This should work with most of the ATAPI devices and with some
SCSI ones. The aim of this tool is to quiet the engine of your CD drive. In most
cases it enhances the read abilities. You can find list of all available
options in @{"Options" LINK UZYWANIE} section.
  If command is accepted by CD drive, it will return "Initialization
successfull" message. If something goes wrong, you'll get message informing
you the initialization was unsuccessful and you'll get return code (eg. $2d),
which means, that command wasn't accepted and your CD drive won't be slowed
down. Program checks if command is being sent to CD drives. If not, you'll get
message about that fact and command won't be sent.
 You must remember that every CD-ROM device sets the maximum read-speed every
time you put compact disk into your CD-ROM. So if you want to slow down the
read-speed, you should execute WolnyCD every time after you insert new CD into your CD
device. The best way to use it is to write small DOS script or add proper
entry to your Main Menu

 It is my first program written for Amiga.

 Caution! I don't take any responsibility for any potential damages 
caused by using my program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MOZLIWOSCI

Features:

- Two ways of setting reading speed: in kB/s (SPEEDRATE) and in "x" (SPEED).
- Support of some CD drive functions like START, STOP, EJECT, LOAD, 
  PREVENT and ALLOW.
- SPEED and SPEEDRATE options work on most of the drives, other functions 
  should work with all optical drives.
- START and STOP can be used with any drive (for example HDD).
- Controled from CLI or by tooltypes.
- AmigaOS 68k, OS4 and MorphOS versions.
- Supports locale.
- Attached sources lets you port WolnyCD to other systems (Amiga-like 
  of course:))
- Uses device name & unit or drive/volume name.  

@ENDNODE

@NODE UZYWANIE

Args & ToolTypes

DEVICE/A/K      - You can set device ID (default: scsi.device)
UNIT/A/N        - CD unit (default: 1)
VOLUME/K	- used to call the device after giving its volume name
                (eg. FoundationDC:) or drive name (eg. CD0:). Device and unit
                values are set from volume info (DEVICE/K and
		UNIT/N are ignored). Error 0xFE - volume not found, 0xFD - 
		device not found.
SPEED/N         - Sets the read-speed in "x". 0 set max speed.
                  SPEED value is changed by program to SPEEDRATE using the
		following formula: 
		SPEEDRATE = SPEED * XCAL
TEAC/S          - It changes read-speed for TEAC/JVC SCSI CD-R devices (and
                  compatible). Accepts only speed values: 1, 2, 4, 8, 12.
TOSHIBA/S	- It changes read-speed for TOSHIBA SCSI devices. If you use 
		WolnyCD SPEED<=16 so TOSHIBA set speed SLOW, SPEED>16 or
		SPEED=0 set FAST mode. The speed mode won't be reset after 
		isnerting/ejecting CD.
UPDATE/N	- Interval in seconds between two invocations of two following 
		SPEED options. That option was added due to drives which 
		automatically changes their speed. After using that option, 
		WolnyCD will work in background. You can disable program by 
		pressing CTRL+C or CTRL+D sequences
START/S		- This option enables engine of specified drive. Works also 
		with HDD!
STOP/S		- This option disables engine of specified drive. Works also 
		with HDD!

Caution! START and STOP options won't work with some devices!

SPEEDRATE/N	- Speed rate in kB/s. This option allows to get any drive 
		speed (for example SPEEDRATE=75 is something about 0.5x). 
		You can enter any value but not all drives will set it 
		properly. If drive don't set given SPEED nor SPEEDRATE you 
		can check all available SPEEDRATE values by TEST option. This
		option don't work with TEAC and TOSHIBA option.
STATUS/S	- Displays actual drive status (SPEED, DISC, PREVENT/ALLOW).
		If that option displays wrong information on your drive, 
		please send to me log file with message generated by that 
		option. Caution! SPEED value given in "x" is only rough and 
		can be different from expected one!
TEST/S		- Checks all available values for SPEEDRATE option by setting 
		all possible values from 10560 (about 60x) to 0. Before you 
		start TEST please enter some disc into drive and wait a moment
	        to stabilize work of the drive. During the test program displays
		all values of SPEEDRATE which caused changes in status 
		mechanism. No value means that your drive cannot be slowdown
		(or interprets STATUS option wrongly). This option don't work
		with TEAC and TOSHIBA option.
QUIET/S		- Disables displaying any messages.
EJECT/S		- Ejects tray.
LOAD/S		- Loads tray.
PREVENT/S	- Blocks EJECT button in drive. After that you can't eject 
		disc without using ALLOW option.
ALLOW/S		- Unblocks EJECT button in drive.
XCAL/N		- Calibrates speed in "x". by default 1x = 176kB/s. But 
		sometimes results returned by STATUS and TEST options are 
		wrong (for example speeds 9x, 13x or 25x). In other case 
		using SPEED=8 will set 4x speed (or vice versa). That means
		that manufacturer of your CD drive assumes other value for
		1x. In that cases you can set it changing XCAL between 175 
		and 177. Other values aren't excluded, but depends from your
		drive.

 If you want to use blizzppc.device, unit 3 and speed 16x please enter:

    WolnyCD device=blizzppc.device unit=3 speed=16


ToolTypes:

 All options available via tooltypes are identically as CLI ones. And 
additionally:

WINDOW		- parameters of messages window, default - 
CON:20/20/500/200/WolnyCD//CLOSE/WAIT


 When you use two mutually excluded options (for example LOAD and EJECT) 
only one of them will be executed.

 Caution! Drives require some time to react. So please use 
earlier mentioned options after drive will stabilize their work. If you 
send option too early it may not take effect, for example option SPEED 
won't take any effect just after closing tray, STATUS will return information
about last settings, etc.

GUI:

 A simple GUI has been added. It requires Argue (Aminet SET4 util/sys or
CyberQT/CyberAVI archive (gfx/show)). GUI can be copied in any place you
want. If WolnyCD exists somewhere else than C: directory, you should define
a path to it. It can be done by GUI ToolTypes
eg. COMMAND=Work:Disc/WolnyCD/WolnyCD.

@ENDNODE


@NODE SZTUCZKI

Tips and tricks:

   When you encounter any problems with reading your CD discs please try 
to set reading speed as low as possible. After CD drive passes troubled 
place you can set speed again to higher value (even during reading process).
   If your CD drive don't react to speed limit settings or minimal 
settable speed is high, there is also trick which will let you read 
troubled areas. Use STOP and next to it START to your CD drive (if your 
drive don't spin up CD automatically). Drive will start reading disc 
"on spinning up" and often those couple seconds are enough to reach maximum 
speed to read successfully troubled area.
   If you want to manage more than one device from WB (by clicking on 
icon) you don't need to change your tooltypes or make 
backup copies of WolnyCD. Just make Project icons and as "Default tool" 
enter path to WolnyCD executable file. Now you only need to set proper 
tooltypes for that icons and put them into WBStartup drawer, dock, etc. 
Examples you will find in Icons drawer.

@ENDNODE


@NODE KONIEC

 Project WolnyCD is now finished. I will apply some fixes eventually. My 
next project will be WolnyCD_CX which will work as commodity. I'll try 
to put into it all options from WolnyCD. Additionally after putting disc into drive
it will automatically set earlier given speed.

Sources of this tool have been attached. Doing that I would like to thank
all the programmers whose sources I used. I think that these sources will help  
beginners. Sources consist procedures and functions concerning handling CLI 
parameters, tooltypes, SCSI and locale.

